{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564104"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:09:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:09:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16938"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17624574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17624574"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:19:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:19:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16938"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16938"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.06,0.24,0.63,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9628"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67837"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9628"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16938"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53302"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"18"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1027"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3026"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22712"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30623"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67837","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67837"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic expressing suicidal thoughts. He works as a primary school bus driver and has been feeling increasingly depressed over the past month following relationship difficulties. He describes specific plans to end his life and admits to rehearsing these plans. He has a history of depression five years ago that resolved with counselling. He takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed with vital signs within normal limits. He agrees to voluntary psychiatric admission for safety.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate approach regarding his fitness to drive?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Allow him to continue driving if he feels capable","Allow driving for personal use only","Review in two weeks to reassess fitness to drive","Report to the Driver Licensing Authority and advise immediate cessation of driving","Permit driving with a co-driver present"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case highlights the critical medicolegal obligations healthcare providers have regarding fitness to drive assessments. The patient presents with acute suicidal ideation with specific plans, which poses an immediate risk to both himself and others. As a commercial driver responsible for children\u0027s safety, the risks are particularly significant and include potential deliberate self-harm using the vehicle, impaired concentration and judgment affecting driving ability, and risk to vulnerable passengers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReport to the Driver Licensing Authority and advise immediate cessation of driving\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct approach. Healthcare providers have both an ethical and legal obligation to report medical conditions that could affect driving safety under Australian law. This obligation overrides patient confidentiality when public safety is at risk. If the patient refuses to stop driving despite medical advice, the healthcare provider must still notify the licensing authority immediately and document this in the medical record. The authority can then take appropriate regulatory action to suspend the licence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllow him to continue driving if he feels capable\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially dangerous. Self-assessment of fitness to drive is not reliable in acute mental illness, and the driver\u0027s judgment may be impaired by their current mental state. There is also potential liability for the healthcare provider if an incident occurs after allowing continued driving.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPermit driving with a co-driver present\u003C/strong\u003E is not an acceptable solution for commercial drivers with acute psychiatric conditions. A co-driver cannot prevent deliberate actions or compensate for impaired judgment and concentration. This approach does not meet regulatory requirements for commercial driving standards.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReview in two weeks to reassess fitness to drive\u003C/strong\u003E delays necessary action and puts public safety at risk. When there is an immediate risk identified, there is a duty of care to act promptly. Delaying action could result in preventable harm and potential liability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllow driving for personal use only\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as the patient requires immediate psychiatric admission and is not currently fit to drive any vehicle. Healthcare providers must report to the licensing authority regarding both commercial and private driving when safety is compromised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to current standards, commercial drivers with severe depression/suicidal ideation require a minimum three-month non-driving period after full recovery, with support from a mental health specialist before return to commercial driving can be considered. The Driver Licensing Authority makes the final decision about licence status. During this period, the patient should receive appropriate mental health treatment and regular review of their condition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Healthcare providers have a legal obligation to report medical conditions that affect driving safety to the Driver Licensing Authority.","Acute suicidality requires immediate cessation of commercial driving duties.","The minimum non-driving period for severe depression/suicidal ideation is 3 months after recovery with specialist support.","If a driver refuses to stop driving despite medical advice, the healthcare provider must report this to the Driver Licensing Authority immediately."],"references":["Austroads. Assessing Fitness to Drive for Commercial and Private Vehicle Drivers [Internet]. 2022. Available at: https://austroads.com.au","Australian Government. Duty of Disclosure for Medical Practitioners [Internet]. Available at: https://www.nhvr.gov.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53302"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16938"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53302","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53302"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-07T11:06:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-07T11:09:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9628"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67837"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id